eller deliberately experimented with different media and their forms - with genres from both literature and the fine arts. The objective of this volume is to trace the various intermedial and transmedial connections in Keller's oeuvre, focusing on the processes of literary and social institutionalization that accompanied his experiments with form and genre.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aFormalismus. 4aGattungstheorie. 4aInstitutionentheorie. 4aLiteraturtheorie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  aFormalism.  agenre theory.  ainstitutional theory.  aliterary theory.1 aBerndt, Frauke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerndt, Frauke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBorghardt, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoléczy, Endre M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKammer, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeck, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoepnick, Lutz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipkin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenninghaus, Winfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMücke, Dorothea von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Dominik